{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474426"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:21:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:21:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12178"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12178"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.21,0.56,0.05,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38326"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4706"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22795"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7430"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41020"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38326"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 13-year-old boy is brought to the emergency department with a fever, productive cough with green phlegm and easy bruising. He has had daily fevers for the past five days with only mild alleviation with paracetamol and ibuprofen. His medical history is significant for meconium ileus shortly after birth and was diagnosed with cystic fibrosis. He has had oily and greasy stools all his life and has recurrent sinopulmonary infections requiring antibiotics 3-4 times per year. The coagulation study reveals a prothrombin time of 25 sec (ref. 10 - 13 sec) and an activated partial thromboplastin time of 35 sec (ref. 25 - 40 sec).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following coagulation factors is most likely to be abnormal in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Factor V","Factor VIII","Factor VII","Factor XII","Factor XIII"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with cystic fibrosis is likely to have a deficiency in vitamin K. Patients with cystic fibrosis have pancreatic insufficiency which leads to fat malabsorption, including fat-soluble vitamins A, D, E, and K.Vitamin K deficiency will lead to a decrease in vitamin K-dependent factors\u003Cstrong\u003E (II, VII, IX, X)\u003C/strong\u003E and an increase in prothrombin time. \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor V\u003C/strong\u003E is not dependent on vitamin K for activation and is unlikely to lead to an increased prothrombin time. \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor VIII \u003C/strong\u003Eis part of the intrinsic pathway and does not affect prothrombin time. \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor XII \u003C/strong\u003Eis part of the intrinsic pathway and is not vitamin K-dependent.\u003Cstrong\u003E Factor XIII \u003C/strong\u003Eis the last step of the clotting cascade, and it functions to stabilize the clot. Mutations of the F13A1 or the F13b gene result in deficient levels of functional factor XIII, which causes blood clots to be weak and unstable resulting in a fast breakdown.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cystic fibrosis (CF) is an inherited genetic disorder with multiorgan involvement. Gastrointestinal tract dysfunction leads to fat and fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K) malabsorption and deficiency of these vitamins.","The vitamin K-dependent coagulation factors are factors II, VII, IX, and X."],"references":["Jagannath VA, Fedorowicz Z, Thaker V, Chang AB. Vitamin K supplementation for cystic fibrosis. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2015 Jan 18;1:CD008482."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22795"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12178"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22795"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-22T11:45:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-23T07:52:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4706"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38326"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"i